description:
Unhandled promise rejections terminate the Node.js process (since v15). Every promise chain needs a .catch(), and every async function call needs try/catch or a .catch() on the returned promise. Set a global safety net, but don't rely on it:

process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason, promise) => {
  logger.error('Unhandled rejection', { reason });
  process.exit(1);
});

This global handler is a last resort — fix the root cause by handling rejections at the call site.

AbortController is the standard way to cancel async work — fetch requests, timers, streams, and custom operations. Pass an AbortSignal to anything long-running so callers can cancel it:

async function fetchWithTimeout(url, timeoutMs = 5000) {
  const controller = new AbortController();
  const timeout = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), timeoutMs);
  try {
    const res = await fetch(url, { signal: controller.signal });
    return await res.json();
  } finally {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
  }
}

Node.js built-ins like fs, http, and timers all support AbortSignal natively.

Never read an entire file or HTTP response into memory when you can stream it. Buffering large data causes memory spikes, GC pressure, and OOM crashes under load. Use pipeline() from node:stream/promises for safe stream composition with automatic error handling and cleanup:

import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';
import { createGzip } from 'node:zlib';

await pipeline(
  createReadStream('input.log'),
  createGzip(),
  createWriteStream('input.log.gz')
);

pipeline() destroys all streams on error — no leaked file descriptors.

Production servers must shut down cleanly — stop accepting new connections, finish in-flight requests, close database pools, then exit. Without this, deploys cause dropped requests and data corruption:

function gracefulShutdown(server, db) {
  let shuttingDown = false;
  const shutdown = async (signal) => {
    if (shuttingDown) return;
    shuttingDown = true;
    console.log(`${signal} received, shutting down...`);
    server.close();
    await db.end();
    process.exit(0);
  };
  process.on('SIGTERM', () => shutdown('SIGTERM'));
  process.on('SIGINT', () => shutdown('SIGINT'));
}

Set a hard timeout (e.g., 30s) to force exit if cleanup stalls.

Fail fast if required environment variables are missing. Don't let the process start and fail 10 minutes later when it first tries to connect to a database. Validate at the top of your entry point:

function requireEnv(name) {
  const value = process.env[name];
  if (!value) {
    console.error(`Missing required env var: ${name}`);
    process.exit(1);
  }
  return value;
}

const config = {
  dbUrl: requireEnv('DATABASE_URL'),
  port: Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000,
  nodeEnv: process.env.NODE_ENV || 'development',
};

Export a frozen config object — never read process.env directly in business logic.

Never use readFileSync, writeFileSync, or any *Sync method in request handlers. They block the entire event loop — no other request can be processed until the I/O completes. One slow disk read blocks every connected client:

// BAD — blocks the event loop
app.get('/config', (req, res) => {
  const data = fs.readFileSync('config.json', 'utf8');
  res.json(JSON.parse(data));
});

// GOOD — non-blocking
app.get('/config', async (req, res) => {
  const data = await fs.promises.readFile('config.json', 'utf8');
  res.json(JSON.parse(data));
});

Sync methods are acceptable at startup for loading config before the server starts listening.

Create typed error classes instead of throwing generic Error objects. This enables precise catch handling, proper HTTP status mapping, and structured logging:

class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(message, code, statusCode = 500) {
    super(message);
    this.name = this.constructor.name;
    this.code = code;
    this.statusCode = statusCode;
  }
}

class NotFoundError extends AppError {
  constructor(resource, id) {
    super(`${resource} ${id} not found`, 'NOT_FOUND', 404);
  }
}

class ValidationError extends AppError {
  constructor(message, fields) {
    super(message, 'VALIDATION_ERROR', 400);
    this.fields = fields;
  }
}

Catch by class: if (err instanceof NotFoundError) — not by message string matching.

Node.js ships a capable test runner since v18. Zero dependencies, native TypeScript support (--experimental-strip-types), and fast startup. Use it before reaching for Jest or Vitest:

import { describe, it, mock } from 'node:test';
import assert from 'node:assert/strict';

describe('UserService', () => {
  it('creates a user with hashed password', async () => {
    const hash = mock.fn(() => 'hashed');
    const service = new UserService({ hash });
    const user = await service.create('alice', 'pass');
    assert.equal(user.name, 'alice');
    assert.equal(hash.mock.calls.length, 1);
  });
});

Run with: node --test --test-reporter spec

Never interpolate user input into shell commands. This is command injection — the #1 server-side vulnerability:

// DANGEROUS — command injection
const { exec } = require('child_process');
exec(`git log --author="${userInput}"`);
// userInput = '"; rm -rf / #' → catastrophic

// SAFE — use array form, bypasses the shell entirely
import { execFile } from 'node:child_process';
execFile('git', ['log', `--author=${userInput}`]);

Rules: use execFile/spawn (not exec/execSync), never set shell: true with user data, validate and sanitize all inputs. If you need a shell, use a whitelist of allowed values.

Use Node.js built-in crypto correctly — don't install third-party packages for basics:

import { randomUUID, scryptSync, timingSafeEqual, randomBytes } from 'node:crypto';

// Generate IDs
const id = randomUUID(); // v4 UUID, cryptographically random

// Hash passwords (scrypt is memory-hard, resistant to GPU attacks)
const salt = randomBytes(16);
const hash = scryptSync(password, salt, 64);

// Compare secrets (constant-time, prevents timing attacks)
const isValid = timingSafeEqual(
  Buffer.from(providedToken),
  Buffer.from(storedToken)
);

Never use MD5/SHA for passwords. Never compare secrets with === (timing leak). Never use Math.random() for security-sensitive values.

An EventEmitter that emits 'error' with no listener crashes the process with an uncaught exception. This applies to streams, HTTP servers, database connections, and any custom emitter:

// This WILL crash if the file doesn't exist
const stream = fs.createReadStream('missing.txt');
// Fix: always attach an error handler
stream.on('error', (err) => {
  logger.error('Stream failed', { error: err.message });
});

// For custom emitters, consider a default error handler:
class MyService extends EventEmitter {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.on('error', (err) => {
      // Prevents crash if consumer forgets to listen
      console.error('Unhandled service error:', err);
    });
  }
}

Rule: if you create it or receive it, listen for 'error' on it.

Use structured JSON logging instead of console.log in production. Structured logs are parseable by log aggregators (Datadog, CloudWatch, ELK) and support filtering, alerting, and correlation:

// Minimal structured logger (no dependencies)
const log = (level, message, meta = {}) => {
  const entry = JSON.stringify({
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
    level,
    message,
    ...meta,
  });
  process.stdout.write(entry + '\n');
};

log('info', 'Request handled', {
  method: 'GET',
  path: '/users',
  duration: 42,
  statusCode: 200,
});

Always include: timestamp, level, message, request ID. Never log secrets, tokens, or passwords.

An empty catch block hides failures and makes debugging impossible. Every catch must do something meaningful — log, rethrow, return a default, or translate the error:

// BAD — silent failure, impossible to debug
try {
  await sendEmail(user);
} catch (e) {}

// GOOD — log and continue (if email is non-critical)
try {
  await sendEmail(user);
} catch (err) {
  logger.warn('Email send failed', { userId: user.id, error: err.message });
}

// GOOD — rethrow with context
try {
  await db.query(sql);
} catch (err) {
  throw new AppError(`Query failed: ${err.message}`, 'DB_ERROR', 500);
}

If you genuinely don't care about the error, add a comment explaining why.

AsyncLocalStorage provides implicit context propagation through async call chains — no need to pass requestId, userId, or tracing data through every function parameter:

import { AsyncLocalStorage } from 'node:async_hooks';

const requestContext = new AsyncLocalStorage();

// Middleware: set context per request
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const store = { requestId: randomUUID(), userId: req.user?.id };
  requestContext.run(store, next);
});

// Anywhere in the call stack:
function getRequestId() {
  return requestContext.getStore()?.requestId;
}

// Logger automatically includes request ID
const log = (level, msg, meta) => {
  const ctx = requestContext.getStore() || {};
  console.log(JSON.stringify({ ...ctx, level, msg, ...meta }));
};

This is how APM tools and logging frameworks implement automatic trace correlation.
